Rawat Piasai : Fungicide Applications for Controlling Root and Stem Rot and Postharvest Fruit Rot Diseases of Monthong' Durian. Master of Science (Plant Pathology), Major Field: Plant Pathology, Department of Plant Pathology. 

Thesis Advisor: Assistant Professor Netnapis Khewkhom, Dr.rer.nat. 

Academic Year 2020 

Root and stem rot as well as fruit rot diseases are the serious problem in durian production for domestic and export. The objective of this research were studied the efficacy of fungicides for controlling durian diseases. Diseased samples of Monthong durian were collected from orchard from Tha Mai district, Chanthaburi province. Tissue transplanting method was used for fungal isolation. Fungal sporulation was induced by baiting technique. Identification of the species was based on morphological characteristics when grown on potato dextrose agar and potato carrot agar mixed with antibiotics. Pathogenicity of fungal isolates were tested on leaves, stems and fruits. The results showed that Phytophthora palmivora was isolated from lesion on leaves and stems, while Fusarium solani, Lasiodiplodia theobromae and Phomopsis sp. were isolated from lesion on fruits. The efficacy of fungicides to inhibit the mycelial growth of pathogens were evaluated. Different concentrations of dimethomorph (10, 100, 1,000 and 10,000 ppm) inhibited $1 0 0 \%$ on the mycelial growth of $P$ palmivora. Two premixed fungicides, prochloraz $4 0 \% +$ propiconazole $9 \%$ W/V EC and azoxystrobin $12 \% +$ tebuconazole $20 \%$ w/V SC were the most effective in mycelial growth inhibition of F. solani, L. theobromae and Phomopsis sp. when compare with metalaxyl. In the greenhouse found that dimethomorph at the rate of 1 $\mathrm { m l / L }$ by foliar spray or soil drench could control stem rot disease of durian ranging from 51.60- $5 7 . 2 0 \%$ , which is a statistically significant difference when compared with metalaxyl. Moreover, prochloraz $4 0 \% +$ propiconazole $9 \%$ W/V EC and/or azoxystrobin $12 \%$ +tebuconazole $20 \%$ w/V SC at the rate of $1 5 ~ \mathrm { m l / 2 0 L }$ by dipping fruits exhibited strong control durian fruit rot caused by. F. solani $( 9 3 . 0 1 \%$ and $67 \%$ ) and Phomopsis sp. $9 5 . 1 0 \%$ and $7 4 . 3 5 \%$ , but could not control. $L$ theobromae.

The process begins with harvesting, which takes place approximately 140-150 days after the flowers bloom. The fruit is cut above the peduncle and placed on a container or plastic sheet. At the packing house, the fruit undergoes trimming and is then cleaned using an air blower. Next is sorting, where fruits with similar characteristics are grouped together and any subpar produce is discarded. This is followed by sizing and grading, which categorizes the fruit into three quality levels: special, first, and second. To prevent rot, the fruit is dipped in a fungicide solution, commonly using chemicals such as Prochloraz, Azoxystrobin, or Propiconazole. After this treatment, the fruit is packaged. The process then splits into two paths: for export, the fruit is stored in containers at 14 degrees Celsius for shipment, such as a 9-day trip to China. For domestic consumption, it is transported by pickup truck and stored at room temperature.

Symptoms of a disease are shown on various parts of a durian plant. The leaf (A) displays a dark lesion with a yellow halo and numerous small yellow spots. The tree trunk (B) shows a large, darkened patch on its bark. In a more advanced stage (C), the damaged bark reveals discolored and decaying inner wood. The fruit itself (D) is shown cracked open, with evidence of rot and discoloration on its spiky husk.

An experimental procedure is shown in six steps. First, durian leaves are washed and cleaned. Second, the leaves are cut, boiled for one minute, and transferred to a culture dish. Third, a 1:1 mixture of tap water and natural pond water is boiled and allowed to cool. Fourth, a fungal culture is grown on PDA medium for 7 days. Fifth, pieces of the fungal agar and the boiled leaves are placed in a culture dish, the prepared water is added, and it is incubated at room temperature. Finally, the structure of the fungus that has grown from the plant tissue is observed under a microscope.

A scientific process is shown in six steps for inoculating a leaf with a fungus. First, a fungus is cultured on a PDA medium for 7 days. Second, a 0.5-centimeter plug is cut from the fungal culture using a sterilized cork borer. Third, a wound is made on the midrib of a durian leaf, and its stem is wrapped with water-soaked cotton. Fourth, the fungal agar plug is transferred onto the wound of the leaf. Fifth, the inoculated leaves are placed in a clear plastic box to incubate in humid conditions at room temperature. The final step is to record the symptoms and severity of the resulting disease on the leaf, which shows brown lesions.

The procedure for inoculating a durian seedling involves four steps. First, a knife is used to make a 1-centimeter long incision in the bark, 10 centimeters above the base of the plant. Second, a sterilized 0.5-centimeter diameter cork borer is used to cut a fungal mycelial plug and transfer it into the prepared wound. Third, the inoculated part of the stem is wrapped with clear plastic. Finally, the inoculation is incubated at room temperature for 24 hours, after which the plastic is removed, and the symptoms and severity of the disease are recorded.

The experimental procedure for studying disease in durian begins with selecting fruits free from disease and insect damage, which are then dipped in a 10% Clorox solution for one minute. After preparing test solutions of various concentrations, the durians are dipped in these for three minutes and air-dried. A wound is created in the rind using a cork borer, which is then inoculated with a disease-causing fungal agar and sealed with the removed piece of rind. The fruit is incubated under humid, room-temperature conditions for 24 hours. For observation, the durians are split into two groups: one portion is kept at room temperature to record disease incidence and severity, while the second portion is packed four per cardboard box and stored in a container at 14°C for similar observation.

The morphology of various fungi is presented through a series of macroscopic and microscopic images. One specimen grown on a PDA medium shows a white, cottony colony (A). Microscopically, it features elongated, curved macroconidia at a 10 µm scale (B) and circular chlamydospores at a 5 µm scale (C). A second fungal culture on PDA presents a dark, grayish-black colony (D). Its microscopic structures are dark brown, oval, and septate conidia, shown at a 20 µm scale (E and F). A third culture on PDA displays a colony with a white center and grayish concentric rings (G). Under the microscope, this fungus reveals a dense mass of conidiophores (H) and slender, filamentous conidia (I), both observed at a 20 µm scale.

(A-C) Fusarium solani, (D-F) Lasiodiplodia theobromae l (G-1) Phomopsis sp.

The rows list concentrations in parts per million (ppm), ranging from 0.01 to 10,000, plus a control group. The columns are organized by time (3, 5, 7, 9, and 12 DDA, which may stand for 'Days After Application') and are subdivided into DMT/DMT2 and MTL readings. The data cell format is complex (e.g., '27.0041.77cd'); this analysis focuses on the primary numerical values. The DMT/DMT2 substance shows a strong dose-dependent effect, reaching a consistent 100% value at all concentrations of 10 ppm and higher, across all time points. In contrast, the MTL substance shows significantly lower and more variable results. For MTL, values are often 0% and peak at 53.45% (at 10,000 ppm, 7 DDA). The control group's values are low, increasing from 2.00% to 8.5% over the observed period. Statistical rows indicate significant results via an F-Test and provide the Coefficient of Variation (CV%). In summary, the DMT/DMT2 substance appears highly effective at concentrations of 10 ppm and above, while the MTL substance is considerably less effective.

This table displays the efficacy of different chemical treatments against three types of fungi, measured at three different time points. The data is presented as a percentage of an undefined metric, 'AmseUa', which is likely fungal inhibition. The rows detail the treatments, including PCR (Prochloraz), PCZ (Propiconazole), and MTL (Metalaxyl), at various concentrations in parts per million (ppm), along with a control group. The columns are grouped by days after application (7, 9, and 12 DAA) and further subdivided by the fungal species: Fusarium solani (Fus), Lasiodiplodia theobromae (Las), and Phomopsis sp. (Pho). Many data cells contain poorly formatted numbers, appearing to combine multiple values. For instance, '60.174.34d' is interpreted as a mean and standard deviation. Overall, PCR and PCZ treatments show high efficacy, frequently reaching 100%, especially at higher concentrations. For example, at 7 DAA, PCR at 2,450 ppm and above achieved 100% against all three fungi. In contrast, the MTL treatment at 6,250 ppm demonstrated significantly lower efficacy, with values ranging from 62.96% down to 0% at 12 DAA against 'Las'. The control group consistently shows low baseline values, typically below 9%. The main takeaway is that Prochloraz and Propiconazole are highly effective against the tested fungi, while Metalaxyl is largely ineffective.

text.text_translated:
The results compare the growth of three fungal species—Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis—at 7 and 12 days post-inoculation (DDA) under different chemical treatments. A combination of PCR and PCZ was tested at ten different concentrations, increasing from 245 ppm to 9,800 ppm. These were compared against a control group with no treatment and a group treated with MTL at 6,250 ppm. At both 7 and 12 DDA, the control groups show significant fungal colony growth. In contrast, the PCR + PCZ treatment demonstrates a clear dose-dependent inhibitory effect; as the concentration of PCR + PCZ increases, the growth of Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis is progressively reduced. At the highest concentrations, fungal growth is almost completely suppressed. The results at 12 DDA confirm this trend, with more developed colonies in the control and lower-concentration groups, while high concentrations of PCR + PCZ maintain their suppressive effect.

Overall, the 'AZx' and 'TBU' treatments demonstrate strong, dose-dependent efficacy, particularly at higher concentrations, while the 'MTL' treatment is shown to be largely ineffective.

The growth of three fungal species—Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis—was observed in petri dishes at 7 and 12 days after inoculation (DDA) under several treatment conditions. A primary treatment, AZX + TBU, was applied at concentrations ranging from 162.5 ppm to 6,500 ppm. For comparison, a treatment with MTL at 6,250 ppm and a control group were also monitored. At 7 DDA, higher concentrations of AZX + TBU (1,625 ppm and above) showed significant inhibition of Fusarium and Phomopsis growth. By 12 DDA, while overall growth had increased, the inhibitory effect of higher AZX + TBU concentrations on Fusarium and Phomopsis was still apparent. In contrast, the MTL and control groups exhibited extensive fungal growth for all three species at both observation points.

The results of an experiment on durian fruit show their condition under various treatments and storage environments, observed at 5 and 7 days after application (DAA). The test substances included DMM at rates from 5 to 40, MTL at 50, and CCM at 100, compared against two control groups. The fruits were divided into two sets. Set 1 was maintained at a constant room temperature of 30°C, where the fruits generally remained whole with some discoloration over the 7 days. Set 2 was stored at 14°C and then moved to 30°C; these fruits displayed significant deterioration, including widespread browning and splitting of the husk, particularly at 7 DAA.

This table presents experimental data on the effects of two chemical formulations on three fungal species under two different experimental conditions. The rows detail different concentrations (in ml or g) of two agents, labeled 'Iwsnaes1k 40% + 1w5wIau1lxa 9% w/V EC' and 'MuanBa 25% w/w WP'. The columns are grouped into two main sections with unclear headers ('mwaneaung 30 amrarua' and 'nuinnnaneung 14 omrasua'), each testing the fungi F. solani, L. theobromae, and Phomopsis sp. The numerical values, often followed by a second number and a letter, likely represent a mean, standard deviation, and statistical grouping. For the first formulation, effectiveness against F. solani and Phomopsis sp. generally increases with concentration, reaching 100 in some cases. However, its effect on L. theobromae is consistently low under the first condition and zero under the second. The 'MuanBa' formulation shows moderate to low effectiveness overall. A notable finding is the complete lack of effect on L. theobromae under the second experimental condition for all treatments. The main takeaway is that the efficacy of these treatments is highly dependent on the specific fungus, concentration, and experimental condition, with the first formulation showing high efficacy against F. solani and Phomopsis sp. but not L. theobromae.

text.text_translated:
This experiment evaluates various treatments on durian fruit infected with one of three pathogens: Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, or Phomopsis. The study is divided into two main groups. The first group displays results for fruits kept at a room temperature of 30°C for 7 days after application (DAA). The second group shows results for fruits first stored at 14°C and then placed at 30°C for 7 DAA. Several treatments were tested, including a combination of 'PCR + PCZ' applied at concentrations ranging from 5 to 40 units, 'MTL' at 50 units, and 'CCM' at 100 units. Positive and negative control groups were also included. The visual results for each combination of treatment, pathogen, and storage condition are displayed, showing the varying degrees of fruit decay.

text.text_translated:
0151 17 nasuinsmsunnnsrnta lnsiu $12 \% +$ nyInuTrn $20 \%$ nt%o Fusarium solani Lasiodiplodia theobromae uas Phomopsis sp.  7 3u 

This table presents the percentage of inhibition, labeled 'nAUANlSA (%)', of several treatments against three fungal species: 'F. solani', 'L. theobromae', and 'Phomopsis sp.'. The data is organized under two primary conditions: a 30-day 'shelf life' condition and a 14-day 'storage' condition. The rows detail various treatments, with the main focus on '0 konkaIns1u 12%+ nyln' applied at increasing concentrations from 5 ml to 40 ml. Under the 'shelf life' condition, inhibition of 'F. solani' and 'Phomopsis sp.' generally increased with concentration, rising from 35.62% and 39.83% at 5 ml to 100% at 40 ml for both. The effect on 'L. theobromae' was much lower and did not show a clear trend. Under the 'storage' condition, a similar dose-dependent inhibition was observed for 'F. solani' (increasing from 38.95% to 89.25%) and 'Phomopsis sp.' (from 25.27% to 65.27%). Notably, there was zero inhibition of 'L. theobromae' under the 'storage' condition for all treatments. Statistical data, including an F-Test and Coefficient of Variation (CV%), are provided at the bottom. The main takeaway is that the '0 konkaIns1u' treatment effectively inhibits 'F. solani' and 'Phomopsis sp.' in a dose-dependent manner, but is largely ineffective against 'L. theobromae'.

text.text_translated:
The effects of various test substances on durian fruit infected with Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis are compared under two different storage conditions. The first set of conditions involves placing the fruit at a room temperature of 30°C for 7 days after application (DAA). The second set involves storing the fruit at 14°C before moving it to 30°C for 7 DAA. The test substances include AZX + TBU at increasing usage rates from 5 to 40, MTL at a rate of 50, and CCM at a rate of 100. These treatments are evaluated against two control groups to observe the visual condition of the fruit under each combination of substance, fungal infection, and temperature.

The percentage of disease control for various treatments is evaluated against three pathogens—Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis—under two distinct conditions. Under the first condition at 30°C, most treatments against Fusarium, including PCR+PCZ concentrations from 15 to 40, MTL 50, and CCM 100, showed high disease control between 85% and 100%. Against Phomopsis, nearly all treatments achieved very high control, above 90%. However, all treatments were largely ineffective against Lasiodiplodia, with control below 20%. Under the second condition, involving storage at 14°C for 9 days, treatments against Fusarium generally maintained high efficacy, with control percentages between 70% and 95%. For Phomopsis, treatments also showed significant control, ranging from about 60% to 95%. Consistent with the first condition, all treatments performed poorly against Lasiodiplodia, with disease control below 20%. The negative control showed 0% disease control in all tests.

Disease control percentage is presented under two main temperature conditions. The first condition is at 30°C (self-life), where data is shown in three groups. In the first and third groups, most treatments result in high disease control, generally between 80% and 100%. In the middle group, however, disease control is significantly lower, with most values below 30%. The second condition is at 14°C for 9 days, representing storage and a 30° shelf life. Under this condition, a similar pattern emerges across three groups of data. The first and third groups again show high efficacy, with many treatments achieving 60% to nearly 100% disease control. In contrast, the middle group shows poor performance, with most treatments resulting in less than 25% disease control.

The percentage of disease control for various treatments is evaluated against three pathogens—Fusarium, Lasiodiplodia, and Phomopsis—under two distinct conditions. Under the first condition at 30°C, most treatments against Fusarium, including PCR+PCZ concentrations from 15 to 40, MTL 50, and CCM 100, showed high disease control between 85% and 100%. Against Phomopsis, nearly all treatments achieved very high control, above 90%. However, all treatments were largely ineffective against Lasiodiplodia, with control below 20%. Under the second condition, involving storage at 14°C for 9 days, treatments against Fusarium generally maintained high efficacy, with control percentages between 70% and 95%. For Phomopsis, treatments also showed significant control, ranging from about 60% to 95%. Consistent with the first condition, all treatments performed poorly against Lasiodiplodia, with disease control below 20%. The negative control showed 0% disease control in all tests.

Disease control percentage is presented under two main temperature conditions. The first condition is at 30°C (self-life), where data is shown in three groups. In the first and third groups, most treatments result in high disease control, generally between 80% and 100%. In the middle group, however, disease control is significantly lower, with most values below 30%. The second condition is at 14°C for 9 days, representing storage and a 30° shelf life. Under this condition, a similar pattern emerges across three groups of data. The first and third groups again show high efficacy, with many treatments achieving 60% to nearly 100% disease control. In contrast, the middle group shows poor performance, with most treatments resulting in less than 25% disease control.
